; A `:merge` body must be a pure write: it may use `old`/`new`, call
; primitives, or mint constructor terms, but it must NOT read the live value
; of another (non-constructor) function. Reading `foo` in `bar`'s merge is a
; live-DB read, which seminaive rule execution cannot track, so it is rejected
; at typecheck time in ALL modes (LookupInMergeDisallowed). Previously this was
; silently accepted in normal mode and panicked at the proof encoder's
; `unreachable!`.
(function foo () i64 :no-merge)

(function bar () i64 :merge (foo))
